## EXAMPLE 1.1

This is a very long worked example that exceeds 800 words. It contains a detailed problem statement followed by a comprehensive solution with multiple steps.

## Problem

A company manufactures widgets. The production process involves multiple stages, each with specific quality control requirements. The first stage involves raw material inspection where incoming materials are tested for tensile strength, chemical composition, and dimensional accuracy. Materials failing any test are rejected and returned to the supplier. The second stage is the machining process where raw materials are shaped using CNC machines programmed with precise specifications. Each machine produces parts with tolerances measured in micrometers. The third stage involves assembly where individual components are joined using various methods including welding, bolting, and adhesive bonding. Quality inspectors verify each joint meets structural requirements. The fourth stage is surface treatment including painting, anodizing, or powder coating depending on the end use of the product. Environmental controls ensure consistent coating thickness and adhesion. The fifth stage involves final testing where completed widgets undergo functional testing simulating real-world conditions. Load testing applies forces up to 150 percent of rated capacity. Vibration testing subjects the widget to frequencies ranging from 10 to 2000 Hz. Temperature cycling exposes the product to extremes from minus 40 to plus 85 degrees Celsius. Humidity testing simulates tropical conditions at 95 percent relative humidity. Salt spray testing evaluates corrosion resistance over a 500 hour exposure period. Each test generates data that is recorded in the quality management system for traceability and statistical process control analysis. The company tracks defect rates using control charts and calculates process capability indices. A Six Sigma program targets fewer than 3.4 defects per million opportunities. When defects are detected, a root cause analysis is performed using fishbone diagrams and the five why technique. Corrective actions are documented and verified through follow up audits. Preventive actions are implemented to reduce the likelihood of recurrence. The quality management system is certified to ISO 9001 standards and undergoes annual surveillance audits by an accredited certification body. Management reviews are conducted quarterly to evaluate the effectiveness of the quality system and identify opportunities for improvement. Customer feedback is collected through surveys and complaint tracking systems. Key performance indicators include on time delivery rate, customer satisfaction score, warranty claim rate, and cost of quality as a percentage of revenue. The company benchmarks its performance against industry leaders and participates in quality awards programs. Training programs ensure all employees understand their role in maintaining quality standards. New employees complete an orientation program that includes quality awareness, safety procedures, and process specific training. Ongoing competency assessments verify that skills remain current. Cross training programs enable flexible workforce deployment during peak demand periods. The company invests in advanced measurement equipment including coordinate measuring machines, optical comparators, and surface roughness testers. Calibration of all measurement equipment is performed at scheduled intervals traceable to national standards. Measurement system analysis studies verify that measurement processes are adequate for their intended purpose. Statistical methods including gauge repeatability and reproducibility studies ensure measurement uncertainty is acceptable relative to product tolerances.

## Solution

Given the multi stage production process, we need to calculate the overall yield. Let each stage have the following individual yields: Stage 1 raw material inspection has a yield of 98 percent. Stage 2 machining has a yield of 96 percent. Stage 3 assembly has a yield of 97 percent. Stage 4 surface treatment has a yield of 99 percent. Stage 5 final testing has a yield of 95 percent. The overall yield is the product of all individual stage yields. Overall yield equals 0.98 times 0.96 times 0.97 times 0.99 times 0.95. Calculating step by step: 0.98 times 0.96 equals 0.9408. Then 0.9408 times 0.97 equals 0.912576. Then 0.912576 times 0.99 equals 0.903450. Finally 0.903450 times 0.95 equals 0.858278. Therefore the overall first pass yield is approximately 85.8 percent. This means that about 14.2 percent of all units started will have at least one defect detected during the production process. The cost of quality analysis shows that prevention costs account for 25 percent of total quality costs, appraisal costs account for 30 percent, internal failure costs account for 35 percent, and external failure costs account for 10 percent. Management should focus on increasing prevention activities to reduce the higher cost categories.

## TRY IT 1.1

A different manufacturing process has four stages with yields of 0.97, 0.95, 0.98, and 0.96. Calculate the overall first pass yield.

